== Sonohyan-utaki Ishimon == Located between {{ill|Kankaimon|ja|歓会門|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankaimon|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and [[:en:Shureimon|Shureimon]] at [[:en:Shuri Castle|Shuri Castle]], the '''Sonohyan-utaki Ishimon''' (園比屋武御嶽石門) serves as the {{ill|Haisho|ja|拝所|lt=worship site|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haisho|qq=}} of the utaki. This stone gate was built in [[:en:1519|1519]] during the reign of {{ill|King Shō Shin|ja|尚真|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/King Shō Shin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 尚真王}}, the third monarch of the {{ill|Second Shō Dynasty|ja|第二尚氏王統|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Second Shō Dynasty|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 第二尚氏}}. It is said to have been established by {{ill|Sai Tō|ja|西塘|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sai Tō|qq=}}, who was brought to Shuri by {{ill|Ōzato Aji|ja|大里親方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōzato Aji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} after the {{ill|Oyake Akahachi Rebellion|ja|オヤケアカハチの乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oyake Akahachi Rebellion|qq=}} in 1500, during which the royal army was sent to the [[:en:Yaeyama Islands|Yaeyama Islands]].
Originally designated as a [[National Treasure of Japan|National Treasure]] on [[January 23, 1933]], the stone gate, along with the royal castle, was severely damaged during the [[Battle of Okinawa]], leading to the loss of its designation. However, in [[:en:1957|1957]], it was reconstructed, and later, parts of the original stonework were incorporated into restoration efforts. Close inspection of the gate reveals areas with differing degrees of wear due to these reconstruction efforts. In [[:en:1972|1972]], the gate was re-designated as an [[Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]]. In [[2000]], along with the [[:en:Shuri Castle|Shuri Castle ruins]], it was included in the [[:en:Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryukyu|Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryukyu]], a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site (UNESCO)|World Heritage Site]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Heritage Committee Inscribes 61 New Sites on World Heritage List |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/184/ |website=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |access-date=2022-05-10 |language=en |first=UNESCO World Heritage |last=Centre}}</ref>.
Additionally, the {{ill|Kunigami-utaki|ja|国仲御嶽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunigami-utaki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 六山}} on Taketomi Island, also founded by Sai Tō, enshrines the deity of Sonohyan-utaki.
